
[1]scrip

   SCRIP, n. [This belongs to the root of gripe, our vulgar grab, that is,
   to seize or press.]

   A small bag; a wallet; a satchel. David put five smooth stones in a
   scrip. 1Sam. 17. Matt. 10.

          SCRIP, n. [L. scriptum, scriptio, from scribo, to write.]

   A small writing, certificate or schedule; a piece of paper containing a
   writing.

   Bills of exchange cannot pay our debts abroad, till scrips of paper can
   be made current coin.

   A certificate of stock subscribed to a bank or other company, or of a
   share of other joint property, is called in America a scrip.
